{"count": 28684, "next": "https://api.acmi.net.au/creators/?page=2064", "previous": "https://api.acmi.net.au/creators/?page=2062", "results": [{"id": 21291, "name": "Dianne Jackson", "roles_in_work": [{"id": 2648139, "title": "The Snowman", "work_id": 78386, "role": "director", "role_id": 938, "is_primary": true}, {"id": 865914, "title": "The Snowman (K)", "work_id": 80738, "role": "director", "role_id": 938, "is_primary": true}], "also_known_as": "", "date_of_birth": "1941-07-28", "date_of_death": "1992-12-31", "genders": [{"id": 5, "name": "Female", "slug": "female"}], "languages": [{"id": 1, "name": "English", "slug": "english"}], "places_of_operation": [{"id": 10, "name": "United Kingdom", "slug": "united-kingdom"}], "biography": "Dianne Jackson (28 July 1941 – 31 December 1992) was an English animation director, best known for The Snowman, made in 1982 and subsequently repeated every Christmas on Channel 4 in the United Kingdom.\nShe had a long career as an animator, and her earliest credit was for The Beatles' Yellow Submarine in 1968. She is particularly noted for recreating the style of the original artists in her animations, for example of Raymond Briggs's picture book, The Snowman.\nShe also directed Granpa by John Burningham in 1989 and was due to direct Raymond Briggs' Father Christmas in 1991, having completed storyboarding for the film, although due to her illness this was directed by Dave Unwin. She also planned the first series of animated adaptations of the tales of Beatrix Potter as The World of Peter Rabbit and Friends. However, she died of cancer on New Year's Eve 1992 at the age of 51. The series episode \"The Tailor of Gloucester\", which was made the year after she died, is \"dedicated to [her] memory\".", "biography_author": "Wikidata", "date_of_biography": "2023-08-01T14:39:18.152604+10:00", "external_links": [{"id": 3881, "uri": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dianne_Jackson"}], "uuid": "47e042fb-13ba-4dd4-8ff3-593e8c435606", "source": {"name": "Vernon", "slug": "vernon"}, "source_identifier": "18089", "external_references": [{"id": 26028, "source": {"name": "Wikidata", "slug": "wikidata"}, "source_identifier": "Q3026284"}, {"id": 28167, "source": {"name": "VIAF", "slug": "viaf"}, "source_identifier": "81830250"}, {"id": 28168, "source": {"name": "LOC Auth", "slug": "loc-auth"}, "source_identifier": "no2003108591"}, {"id": 28169, "source": {"name": "WorldCat", "slug": "worldcat"}, "source_identifier": "lccn-no2003108591"}], "date_modified": "2025-03-05T13:40:20.711487+11:00"}, {"id": 21290, "name": "John Coates", "roles_in_work": [{"id": 2238469, "title": "Father Christmas", "work_id": 92540, "role": "producer", "role_id": 1089, "is_primary": true}, {"id": 1814379, "title": "The Wind in the willows", "work_id": 85456, "role": "producer", "role_id": 1089, "is_primary": true}, {"id": 2282270, "title": "The World of Peter Rabbit and friends", "work_id": 115438, "role": "producer", "role_id": 1089, "is_primary": true}, {"id": 1809429, "title": "The Bear (Animated)", "work_id": 90684, "role": "producer", "role_id": 1089, "is_primary": true}, {"id": 2648138, "title": "The Snowman", "work_id": 78386, "role": "producer", "role_id": 1089, "is_primary": true}, {"id": 1807034, "title": "The Snowman (K)", "work_id": 80738, "role": "producer", "role_id": 1089, "is_primary": true}], "also_known_as": "", "date_of_birth": "07 NOV 1927", "date_of_death": "16 SEP 2012", "genders": [{"id": 9, "name": "Male", "slug": "male"}], "languages": [{"id": 1, "name": "English", "slug": "english"}], "places_of_operation": [{"id": 10, "name": "United Kingdom", "slug": "united-kingdom"}], "biography": "John Coates (7 November 1927 – 16 September 2012) was a British film producer, best known for producing the animated film The Snowman based on the picture book by Raymond Briggs, one of the first animated productions screened on Channel Four and still repeated every year on the channel.\n\nHe co-founded the animation studio TVC (Television Cartoons) London with George Dunning in 1957 and worked on The Beatles's animated feature Yellow Submarine and produced numerous other animated films including When the Wind Blows, Granpa, Father Christmas, The World of Peter Rabbit and Friends and The Bear.\n\nJohn's business partner for many years was Norman David Kauffman, who first worked with him at the age of 16 as a trainee animator. He became a Director of TVC and associated companies in 1999 until his retirement in 2012.\n\nJohn was the nephew of the 1st Baron Rank, and worked within the Rank Organisation after leaving school at Stowe. He had 3 siblings, most notably, Anne V. Coates, Academy Award-winning editor of Laurence of Arabia.\n\nCoates died of cancer at the age of 84 in his home in Kent, England, on 16 September 2012. The Snowman and the Snowdog is dedicated to his memory. Source: Wikidata; 01/08/2023", "biography_author": null, "date_of_biography": "2025-03-05T13:40:20.134344+11:00", "external_links": [{"id": 4361, "uri": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_Coates_(producer)"}], "uuid": "d126d7bd-8ec0-4ef6-8a64-884fb9bf668b", "source": {"name": "Vernon", "slug": "vernon"}, "source_identifier": "22178", "external_references": [{"id": 26038, "source": {"name": "Wikidata", "slug": "wikidata"}, "source_identifier": "Q4250255"}, {"id": 29463, "source": {"name": "VIAF", "slug": "viaf"}, "source_identifier": "305407419"}, {"id": 29464, "source": {"name": "WorldCat", "slug": "worldcat"}, "source_identifier": "viaf-305407419"}], "date_modified": "2025-03-05T13:40:20.134697+11:00"}, {"id": 21289, "name": "Snowman Enterprises", "roles_in_work": [{"id": 865912, "title": "The Snowman (K)", "work_id": 80738, "role": "production company", "role_id": 941, "is_primary": true}, {"id": 2648137, "title": "The Snowman", "work_id": 78386, "role": "production company", "role_id": 941, "is_primary": true}], "also_known_as": "", "date_of_birth": null, "date_of_death": null, "genders": [], "languages": [], "places_of_